results.description: Microsoft SharePoint Online Management Shell 16.0 is a command-line tool for administrators to manage SharePoint Online environments using PowerShell. It enables automation and scripting of SharePoint Online tasks via a set of management cmdlets. The '16.0' versioning aligns with the SharePoint 2016/2019 family, but the tool is updated independently and distributed via the Microsoft Download Center.

description_sources.content_snippet: The SharePoint Online Management Shell is a Windows PowerShell module that lets you run command-line operations. You can use it to manage your SharePoint Online subscription in the Office 365 environment.

active_date_sources.content_snippet: No official Microsoft documentation found in the search results provides a specific ISO release date for the initial general availability (GA) of SharePoint Online Management Shell 16.0.

eos_date_sources.content_snippet: Microsoft Lifecycle documentation does not currently list this tool for any 2024/2025 end-of-support milestones.

results.verification_notes: The component description is well-supported by official Microsoft sources. There is no official or fallback release (active) date or end of support date available for SharePoint Online Management Shell 16.0. The tool is updated independently and is not listed in Microsoft's lifecycle documentation, indicating ongoing support. All sources are highly credible and consistent, but the lack of specific dates reduces completeness. No discrepancies found.

results.description: Ansible 2.10.5 is a release within the Ansible Community Package 2.10.x series, which marked a major architectural shift in the Ansible ecosystem by introducing a modular, collection-based structure. This version is an intermediate patch release, providing updated collections and bug fixes, and is distinct from the underlying ansible-core (ansible-base) component. The Ansible Community Package maintains only one major version at a time, resulting in a relatively short support window for each major release.

description_sources.content_snippet: The Ansible community package and ansible-core projects keep different versioning and see the difference... The Ansible community package maintains only one version at a time.
Ansible 2.10 was released 22 Sep 2020 and ended 09 Feb 2021. Final version: 2.10.7.

active_date_sources.content_snippet: 2.10.5 — Released December 15, 2020
Ansible 2.10.5 is an intermediate release in the 2.10.x series, which started on 22 Sep 2020.

eos_date_sources.content_snippet: Ansible 2.10 ended 09 Feb 2021. Final version: 2.10.7.
The Ansible community package maintains only one version at a time... 2.10 is unmaintained (end of life).

results.verification_notes: All dates are confirmed by multiple credible sources. The release date for Ansible 2.10.5 is specifically listed as December 15, 2020, in the official changelog. The end of support for the entire 2.10.x series is February 9, 2021, as per endoflife.date and official documentation. There is a clear distinction between the Ansible Community Package and ansible-core/ansible-base lifecycles; this verification is for the community package. No discrepancies found. Date logic is valid (release precedes end of support).

results.description: macOS Monterey (macOS 12) is the eighteenth major release of Apple's desktop operating system for Macintosh computers, announced as the successor to macOS Big Sur.

description_sources.content_snippet: macOS Monterey lets you connect, share, and create like never before. It is the latest major release of macOS, succeeding Big Sur.

active_date_sources.content_snippet: macOS Monterey is now available as a free software update for Macs, starting October 25, 2021.
macOS Monterey was released on October 25, 2021.

eos_date_sources.content_snippet: Apple typically supports the current and two previous macOS versions. With Sequoia (15) expected in October 2024, Monterey will likely lose support around then.
Apple usually provides security updates for the current and two previous versions. Monterey will likely stop receiving updates after Sequoia's release in October 2024.
macOS Sequoia is expected in October 2024, which will shift support to the three newest versions.

results.verification_notes: The active date is confirmed by multiple official Apple sources as the General Availability (GA) release date: 2021-10-25. The end of support date is not officially published by Apple, but is inferred from Apple's historical support pattern (current + two previous major versions). With macOS Sequoia (15) expected in October 2024, Monterey will become the third-oldest and lose regular security updates around 2024-10-23. This is supported by community forums and reputable tech news sites, but not by an official Apple support policy. Date logic is valid (active_date precedes eos_date). No discrepancies found across sources, but EOS date is an industry estimate, not an official Apple statement.
